yaweek schedule and map out a reconstruction of the met’s wing for modern and contemporary art considered one of the weaker areas of its collection“there’s no hidden agenda here — nothing anybody should be looking for” she added “it is completely my decision”ms rafferty said she fully supported and has been deeply involved in the met’s new master plan drafted after an extensive study of the museum’s physical plant completed last fall by beyer blinder belle as part of the met’s first comprehensive reexamination of its layout in  years the museum is planning to rebuild the lila acheson wallace wing which holds its collection of modern and contemporary artthe work is not expected to be completed until  another factor that ms rafferty said contributed to her decision“somebody should be in this job who’s going to see it all the way there” she said “i will not be here for the next  years” advertisement continue reading the main story ms rafferty said she was contemplating working in the public sector but had not begun a job search “this is all having to do with me and the met and the next steps will come when they come” she saidthomas p campbell the met’s director and chief executive officer said in an interview “emily has been my closest partner since i became director we’ve worked together very closely and very successfully over the last five and a half years”still as is often the case with highprofile personnel changes speculation immediately arose in the art world that ms rafferty and mr campbell might have had an uneasy relationship newsletter sign up continue reading the main story please verify youre not a robot by clicking the box invalid email address please reenter you must select a newsletter to subscribe to sign up you agree to receive occasional updates and special offers for the new york timess products and services thank you for subscribing an error has occurred please try again later you are already subscribed to this email view all new york times newslett